      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insights\n\n1. **Two dissociation steps only.** Oxalic acid is classified as HвӮӮL (diprotic) in SRD-46, consistent with its two carboxylic acid groups. There is no third ionization.\n\n2. **Unusually strong first acid.** The pKa1 of вҲ’1.2 (at zero ionic strength) is far below that of typical carboxylic acids (~4вҖ“5). The two adjacent electron-withdrawing carbonyl groups strongly stabilize the monoanion HLвҒ», making the first proton very easy to lose. At ionic strength 1.0 M (NaClOвӮ„), pKa1 rises to ~1.04, illustrating the sensitivity of this value to ionic environment.\n\n3. **More typical second dissociation.** The pKa2 of ~3.8 is closer to a normal carboxylic acid, because the existing negative charge on HLвҒ» resists further deprotonation.\n\n4. **Excellent ligand chemistry.** The fully deprotonated oxalate dianion (LВІвҒ») is a powerful bidentate chelator, forming stable complexes with **20 different metals** in SRD-46 (including FeВівҒә, AlВівҒә, CaВІвҒә, CuВІвҒә, UOвӮӮВІвҒә, and ThвҒҙвҒә), with a total of 394 stability-constant measurements. This underpins oxalate's importance in kidney stone formation, soil geochemistry, and industrial metal processing.\n\n---\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46, ligand_8872 вҖ” Ethanedioic acid (Oxalic acid)*",
